<% content_for :title, "Privacy" %>

<div class="l-container">
  <h1><%= multicolor("Privacy") %></h1>

  <p class="m-lede">
    Short version: we don't collect your personal info, we don't track you across
    the web, and there's nothing here to sell. No accounts to play, no names, no
    email, no location, no ad networks, no pixels, no third-party analytics, no
    third parties at all.
  </p>

  <h2>The one cookie</h2>
  <p>
    Playing sets a single anonymous token in your browser — a random string, not
    tied to any identity. It exists so <em>your own</em> stats (your solve rate,
    your emoji cube) work on your device. We couldn't tell you who you are if we
    tried, because we never asked.
  </p>

  <h2>Gameplay stats</h2>
  <p>
    We do record how puzzles go — which words got grouped, how many mistakes,
    whether it was solved — so a puzzle's author can see its stats. That data is
    anonymous and aggregate. No name is attached to it, ever.
  </p>

  <h2>Traffic counts</h2>
  <p>
    We keep basic, anonymous traffic stats so we know the site's alive — which
    pages get visited and where visitors came from (a search engine, a link, an AI
    answer). That's it: <strong>no IP address, no cookies, no personal data, and
    nothing shared with anyone</strong>. It's all first-party, measured on our own
    box — not a single analytics script runs in your browser. This is the honest,
    no-creeping version of knowing whether anyone showed up.
  </p>

  <h2>Creators</h2>
  <p>
    If you sign in to <em>build</em> puzzles, that's an email and a password, used
    only to log you in. It's the only personal thing in the whole system, it's
    yours, and it goes nowhere else.
  </p>

  <h2>Third parties</h2>
  <p>
    None. No trackers, no embeds phoning home, no data shared or sold. The app is
    self-hosted — your gameplay doesn't leave the box it runs on.
  </p>

  <p>
    Questions? <%= link_to "johnhutch.com", "https://johnhutch.com", target: "_blank", rel: "noopener" %>.
  </p>

  <p><%= link_to "← Back to the quartets", root_path %></p>
</div>
